	<item>
		<title>By: Lee_Kirkpatrick</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/technique/string-crossing-exercise-bass-lesson.html#comment-16152</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lee_Kirkpatrick]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Jun 2015 20:16:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=11025#comment-16152</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[I was trying to figure out why Scott&#039;s method might be superior to the usual method -- i.e., practicing the entire line/lick at a slow tempo, and then gradually increasing the speed until you get to the target tempo -- and then I saw a great answer at TalkBass.com: You might have to alter your technique in (perhaps subtle) ways to play something at a higher tempo than at a slower tempo. It occurred to me, for example, that you might be able to play something at a slower tempo using rest strokes, but have to switch to free strokes to play the same thing at the faster target tempo. If you tried to play the whole line/riff slowly, and gradually increased the tempo, you might at some point hit a wall beyond which you just can&#039;t play it any faster -- and you&#039;d never know why. However, if you start from the beginning using Scott&#039;s method, you have to master whatever technique is required to play the notes at tempo right from the start, and then it&#039;s just a matter of adding all the notes.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I was trying to figure out why Scott&#8217;s method might be superior to the usual method &#8212; i.e., practicing the entire line/lick at a slow tempo, and then gradually increasing the speed until you get to the target tempo &#8212; and then I saw a great answer at TalkBass.com: You might have to alter your technique in (perhaps subtle) ways to play something at a higher tempo than at a slower tempo. It occurred to me, for example, that you might be able to play something at a slower tempo using rest strokes, but have to switch to free strokes to play the same thing at the faster target tempo. If you tried to play the whole line/riff slowly, and gradually increased the tempo, you might at some point hit a wall beyond which you just can&#8217;t play it any faster &#8212; and you&#8217;d never know why. However, if you start from the beginning using Scott&#8217;s method, you have to master whatever technique is required to play the notes at tempo right from the start, and then it&#8217;s just a matter of adding all the notes.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
