		<title>By: Alessandro Arcuri</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/technique/string-crossing-exercise-bass-lesson.html#comment-16150</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Alessandro Arcuri]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Jun 2015 19:35:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=11025#comment-16150</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[This lesson would make Billy Sheehan proud! I did translation work at a couple of his seminars and one thing he pointed out is that he&#039;s a good &quot;problem spotter&quot; (and then solver, of course). When you&#039;re trying to pull off a complicated riff or technique, he says it&#039;s no use pushing on if you are clearly struggling with something. He developed his formidable technique because when he encountered a glitch or an obstacle, he was really good at &quot;deconstructing&quot; it, so to speak. Is it the fingering pattern? Is it the string skipping? The plucking hand? Focus on just one issue at a time and then put it back together. It clearly works! ;-)]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>This lesson would make Billy Sheehan proud! I did translation work at a couple of his seminars and one thing he pointed out is that he&#8217;s a good &#8220;problem spotter&#8221; (and then solver, of course). When you&#8217;re trying to pull off a complicated riff or technique, he says it&#8217;s no use pushing on if you are clearly struggling with something. He developed his formidable technique because when he encountered a glitch or an obstacle, he was really good at &#8220;deconstructing&#8221; it, so to speak. Is it the fingering pattern? Is it the string skipping? The plucking hand? Focus on just one issue at a time and then put it back together. It clearly works! ;-)</p>
]]></content:encoded>
